et deus: Mr Roby proposes to read at (which might easily lose its vowel atter actuosa, and change into et) as it introduces a minor premiss in a quasi-syllogistic argument. But where one syllogism is subordinated to another (as in this passage virtus autem—&itur represents the minor premiss in the syllogism of which sine virtute nullo modo is the major, and ne beatus quidem the conclusion) it is not uncommon to omit the signs of opposition between the propositione of the subordinate syllogism ε thus, A, none are happy without virtue, · B, but virtue is active and your God inactive, therefore not virtuous; O, therefore your ‘god is not happy.
